Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is mean squared error?
AI Response

MSE is (1/n) * sum of (predicted - actual)^2. It penalizes large errors heavily and is a standard loss function
for regression tasks, sensitive to outliers.

Example 1.2

User

What is regularization?
AI Response

Regularization adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage model complexity. L1 promotes sparsity; L2
penalizes large weights. Both reduce overfitting.

Example 1.3

User

What is GPT?
AI Response

GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) is an autoregressive language model trained to predict the next
token. GPT-3 and GPT-4 are large-scale versions capable of diverse language tasks.

Example 1.4

User

What is K-means clustering?
AI Response

K-means partitions data into K clusters by iteratively assigning points to the nearest centroid and updating
centroids as the mean of assigned points, minimizing intra-cluster variance.

Example 1.5

User

What is a hyperparameter?
AI Response

A hyperparameter is a configuration setting external to the model—like learning rate or batch size—set
before training and tuned using validation performance.

Example 1.6

User

What is zero-shot learning?
AI Response

Zero-shot learning predicts unseen classes by leveraging semantic relationships or natural language task
descriptions, allowing LLMs to generalize without task-specific training.

Example 1.7

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response



Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.8

User

What is deep learning?
AI Response

Deep learning is a subset of machine learning that uses multi-layered neural networks to learn
representations of data. It excels at tasks like image recognition, NLP, and speech synthesis.

Example 1.9

User

What is feature engineering?
AI Response

Feature engineering creates or transforms input variables using domain knowledge to improve model
performance. It includes scaling, encoding, and creating interaction terms.

Example 1.10

User

What is the vanishing gradient problem?
AI Response

In deep networks, gradients shrink exponentially during backpropagation, preventing early layers from
learning. Solutions include ReLU activations, residual connections, and LSTMs.



